{
  "doc_id": "10955",
  "text": "It should be noted that a microbial population that is defined above the level of the single clone might represent an operational rather than a natural category. Therefore, such an operational taxonomic unit will be limited in its usefulness to a particular study context, and it should be refined or expanded if found inadequate for a specific purpose (Fig. 2) . Some phylogenetic clades might harbor organisms with closely related or even identical 16S rRNA gene sequences but rather different ecophysiological properties [CITATION_1] . Sometimes it may be useful to merge such strains into larger categories, e.g., to study the occurrence of genera associated with particular phytoplankton blooms [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . At other instances it might be necessary to distinguish between closely related strains, e.g., to understand the ecological significance of physiological variability [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] (Fig. 2) .",
